					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">There is also a guarantee to get it made. I mean we all have flash carts and you can get a PCB made for $5 online. Go back to 1986 and how are you going to get a cart made? How are you going to get enough made to make it viable? So the License is a promise with Nintendo. You say we want to make X, Nintendo say &quot;Ok, this is probably going to sell, you make it and we will make the carts&quot;. You make the game, they then test it, if the can see it can be finished and plays well enough, then Nintendo then do the effort to make the Mask ROMS and fire up the forges. <br />The other problem is brand loyalty. If you get a bad Nintendo game, I mean really bad. You look at the Nintendo and say &quot;Why?&quot;, you want to keep the quality to make people think well of your Brand so people want to buy your console again.</div>

